# 1. Run the Initial Setup (Most Important Step)
This command creates the database tables, a superuser (admin) account, and configures the system. You must run this before accessing the web UI.

```bash
docker exec -it kiwi_web /Kiwi/manage.py initial_setup
```

Follow the interactive prompts:
- Create the admin username (e.g., **admin**)
- Provide an email address
- Set a strong password
- Confirm the domain (for a local setup, **localhost** or **127.0.0.1** works)
This step only need to be done once for a fresh installation.

# 2. Access the Web Interface
Once the **initial_setup** finishes successfully:
- HTTP: http://**localhost** (or http://**127.0.0.1**)
- HTTPS (recommended): https://**localhost** (or https://**127.0.0.1**)

Your Docker Compose file maps:
- Host port 80 ü© container 8080 (HTTP)
- Host port 443 ü© container 8443 (HTTPS)

Note on HTTPS: The container uses a self-signed certificate by default. Your browser will show a security warning ? you can accept it for local use. You can download the CA certificate from [localhost](https://localhost/static/ca.crt) to install it in your browser/OS to avoid warnings. [readthedocs](https://kiwitcms.readthedocs.io/en/latest/installing_docker.html)

# 3. Log In
Use the admin credentials you just created during initial_setup.

# 4. Next Steps After Logging In
- Create your first Test Plan ? This is the central object in Kiwi TCMS.
- Add Test Cases to plans.
- Explore the UI ? There are sections for Products, Builds, Test Runs, Bugs, etc.
- Configure your environment (e.g., integrate with bug trackers like GitHub, Jira, Bugzilla).
- Create more users via the Admin panel (if needed).

## Useful Docker Commands
- View logs: docker compose logs -f or docker logs kiwi_web
- Stop everything: docker compose down
- Restart: docker compose restart
- Re-run setup/upgrade later: docker exec -it kiwi_web /Kiwi/manage.py upgrade
- Check container status: docker compose ps

Common Issues & Tips
- If the site doesn't load immediately after up -d, wait 10?30 seconds for the services to fully initialize, then run the initial_setup.
- Check container health with docker compose logs kiwi_web and docker compose logs kiwi_db.
- The database data and uploads are stored in Docker volumes (db_data and uploads), so they persist even if you run docker compose down.
- For production use, consider:
  - Setting up a proper reverse proxy (Nginx/Traefik) with real SSL certificates.
  - Changing default passwords.
  - Backing up volumes regularly.

